\f1\b0 \cf2 It turns out that analogWrite() also works well to control the speed of a motor. However now we need to consider whether our motor is compatible with Arduino\'92s outputs.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 \
Arduino outputs: Voltage and current\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf2 When used as outputs, two things must be considered: the voltage and the current. Our Arduino can deliver 5 v, and at most 40 mA.\
The voltage is determined by Arduino, but the current is determined by whatever we\'92re trying to control. In the case of the LEDs, they only need 20 mA or less. The motor we have might take more than 40 mA. In the worst case, when it\'92s stalled, it might want a 200 mA.\
The important thing to realize is that Arduino does not have the ability to limit this current. It will try to deliver whatever is asked of it,\'a0
\f0\b even if it overheats and damages itself
\f1\b0 .\
If we want to control a device that might take more than 40 mA, we have to use an intermediary.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

